2.25.12722421273801057597930810679778035.report_text:
EXAMINATION: Single-view cervical spine X-ray
FINDINGS:
The lateral single-view X-ray of the cervical spine reveals
multi-level degenerative changes characterized by pronounced
intervertebral disc space narrowing at C5-C6 and C6-C7 levels.
Anterior osteophytic proliferation is observed along the vertebral
bodies from C4 through C7, suggestive of spondylosis. There is no
evidence of acute fracture or subluxation. The alignment maintains
normal lordotic curvature without pathological kyphosis. The facet
joints at multiple levels demonstrate hypertrophic changes, and there
is mild narrowing of the neural foramina bilaterally at C5-C6,
potentially impinging on exiting nerve roots. No soft tissue swelling
is noted anterior to the cervical vertebrae. The prevertebral soft
tissue thickness remains within normal limits. The odontoid process
is intact and well visualized.


IMPRESSION:
Significant cervical spondylosis with marked degenerative disc
disease predominantly at C5-C6 and C6-C7 levels, accompanied by
anterior osteophytosis and facet joint hypertrophy producing mild
foraminal narrowing bilaterally. These degenerative alterations align
with chronic cervical spine degenerative pathology, consistent with
clinical symptoms such as radiculopathy or neck pain. The lack of
acute bony injury or alignment abnormality excludes recent trauma.
Continued clinical correlation and consideration of advanced imaging
may be warranted depending on symptomatology.
Dictated by: Latasha Long Interpreter, M.D.

2.25.13784873364498186558115612498222191.report_text:
EXAMINATION: Abdominal X-ray imaging study.
FINDINGS:
Radiograph reveals mildly dilated small bowel loops with air-fluid
levels suggestive of early partial small bowel obstruction. No free
intraperitoneal air identified. Soft tissues unremarkable. No
evidence of radiopaque calculi or masses.


IMPRESSION:
Findings may represent early or partial small bowel obstruction.
Recommend clinical correlation and possible further imaging if
symptoms worsen.
Dictated by: Michael Harris Interpreter, M.D.

2.25.29675034253164185042723977229677267.report_text:
EXAMINATION: Posteroanterior and lateral chest radiographs
FINDINGS:
The posteroanterior and lateral chest X-ray images reveal clear
visualization of the bony thorax and soft tissues. The
cardiomediastinal silhouette is within normal limits but demonstrates
mild cardiomegaly with a cardiothoracic ratio slightly above 0.5.
Pulmonary vasculature appears somewhat prominent consistent with
chronic pulmonary congestion. There is evidence of increased
interstitial markings bilaterally, suggestive of chronic interstitial
lung disease. No acute consolidation, pleural effusions, or
pneumothorax are identified. The lung volumes are preserved, and
diaphragmatic contours are smooth with normal costophrenic angles. A
few scattered, ill-defined nodular opacities are noted in the right
upper lobe region, measuring less than 1 cm in diameter, which could
represent granulomatous disease or early neoplastic changes. The
trachea is midline and patent. Comparison to prior imaging is not
available at this time.


IMPRESSION:
Findings consistent with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease
demonstrated by increased interstitial markings and chronic pulmonary
vascular congestion. Mild cardiomegaly noted which may correlate with
underlying ischemic heart disease or cardiomyopathy. Scattered small
nodular opacities, particularly in the right upper lobe, warrant
further evaluation with CT imaging to characterize and exclude early
neoplastic processes or granulomatous disease. No acute pulmonary
pathology identified. Recommend clinical correlation and follow-up
imaging as appropriate.
Dictated by: Tara Williams Interpreter, M.D.
